01:51:39.230 --> 01:51:41.530
Sylviane, it's yours.

01:51:42.570 --> 01:51:48.800 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Sylviane A. Diouf: So I'm going
to take you back to the first panel.

01:51:48.800 --> 01:51:52.230
I will be speaking about the
African Muslims were enslaved

01:51:52.230 --> 01:51:53.530
in the Americas.

01:51:53.530 --> 01:51:56.790
And when we look at the situation
today we see that about 7%

01:51:56.790 --> 01:52:02.530
of the Muslims in the United
States are Sub-Saharan Africans.

01:52:02.530 --> 01:52:06.860
But there was a time when they
represented 100% of the Muslims

01:52:06.860 --> 01:52:12.750
in this country as well as in the
Americas at large in the Caribbean.

01:52:12.750 --> 01:52:16.510
Those were the first 400 years.

01:52:16.510 --> 01:52:20.240
Now between the really early
years of the 59 [inaudible]

01:52:20.240 --> 01:52:26.180
until the 1860s hundreds
of thousands

01:52:26.180 --> 01:52:30.240
of Sub-Saharan Muslims were
brought to the Americas.

01:52:30.240 --> 01:52:35.540
There were prisons here but
between 15 and 20% of the 12

01:52:35.540 --> 01:52:42.470
to 15 million Africans were swept
in the Atlantic slave trade.

01:52:42.470 --> 01:52:46.750
About 600,000 Africans
were sent to --

01:52:46.750 --> 01:52:49.900
but they came to the United
States so we can think

01:52:49.900 --> 01:52:56.160
that about 100,000
of them were Muslims.

01:52:56.160 --> 01:53:00.740
Those people were men,
women, children.

01:53:00.740 --> 01:53:05.070
They were [inaudible] Muslims,
farmers, musicians, cattle herders,

01:53:05.070 --> 01:53:10.430
craftspeople, any category
that you can think of.

01:53:10.430 --> 01:53:14.500
But there were also categories
that were specific to the Muslims.

01:53:14.500 --> 01:53:21.920
For example, they were students
and teachers in Koranic schools.

01:53:21.920 --> 01:53:25.790
They were scholars, Imam,

01:53:25.790 --> 01:53:28.400
[inaudible] were memorizers
of the Koran.

01:53:28.400 --> 01:53:30.750
They were judges in
Islamic [inaudible].

01:53:30.750 --> 01:53:34.910
They were political
religious leaders and clerics.

01:53:34.910 --> 01:53:40.270
Some just like Omar [inaudible]
Said were enslaved here mentioned

01:53:40.270 --> 01:53:44.470
that before they were brought
to the Americas they had gone

01:53:44.470 --> 01:53:47.560
to Mecca to make the pilgrimage.

01:53:47.560 --> 01:53:52.760
Some studied in Egypt
also or in Morocco.

01:53:52.760 --> 01:53:57.990
Here, in the Americas and the
Caribbean, they did all the work

01:53:57.990 --> 01:54:01.110
that people were enslaved to do --

01:54:01.110 --> 01:54:06.300
picking cotton, tobacco,
rice, et cetera.

01:54:06.300 --> 01:54:09.910
But there is also evidence
that many Muslims were employed

01:54:09.910 --> 01:54:16.290 position:56%
as professionals, as slave
drivers, as craftspeople, et cetera.

01:54:16.290 --> 01:54:19.950
What -- but there was one
thing that differentiated them

01:54:19.950 --> 01:54:21.360
from the rest of the population.

01:54:21.360 --> 01:54:23.300
Not only the other
people were enslaved,

01:54:23.300 --> 01:54:30.070
but also many of the unslavers,
and this is the fact as mentioned

01:54:30.070 --> 01:54:35.550
by Professor Hunwick that some of
them could read and write in Arabic

01:54:35.550 --> 01:54:40.550
but also in their own language
written in the Arabic script.

01:54:40.550 --> 01:54:44.650
Now it's one thing to
know how to read and write

01:54:44.650 --> 01:54:46.520
and to come here knowing that.

01:54:46.520 --> 01:54:52.290
It's another thing to continue
to do so when you're enslaved.

01:54:52.290 --> 01:55:01.390
And especially in countries that
forbid slaves to read and write.

01:55:01.390 --> 01:55:05.550
So, obviously, even though they
kept their skills in the Americas

01:55:05.550 --> 01:55:09.360
and there are many documents
not only in the United States

01:55:09.360 --> 01:55:13.080
but in Latin America that
mention that slaves --

01:55:13.080 --> 01:55:15.360
I mean Muslims were writing.

01:55:15.360 --> 01:55:16.870
It was a difficult endeavor.

01:55:16.870 --> 01:55:20.880
Of course they could
not buy paper and ink.

01:55:20.880 --> 01:55:24.090 position:56%
It was a very -- it was very hard to
do, not only for financial reasons

01:55:24.090 --> 01:55:27.170
but also because if you were
[inaudible] you were just not

01:55:27.170 --> 01:55:32.100
supposed to do -- buying
ink and paper.

01:55:32.100 --> 01:55:36.210
So we have an example of
Ibrahim [foreign words]

01:55:36.210 --> 01:55:39.540
from Guinea was a slave in
Mississippi for 40 years

01:55:39.540 --> 01:55:44.220 position:56%
and what he did was when he was --
when the people were taking a break,

01:55:44.220 --> 01:55:49.180
he was a cotton picker, he
used to write on the sand

01:55:49.180 --> 01:55:53.550 position:56%
of the plantation just to make sure
that he did not forget how to write.

01:55:53.550 --> 01:55:55.840
But in some other countries,
and maybe here

01:55:55.840 --> 01:55:57.180 position:56%
in the United States also, it's just

01:55:57.180 --> 01:55:59.890
that I haven't found
the documentation,

01:55:59.890 --> 01:56:02.800
people were also making
their own implements.

01:56:02.800 --> 01:56:05.390
They were making ink
as people do in Africa.

01:56:05.390 --> 01:56:13.500
I found an example of people
from Nigeria would be enslaved

01:56:13.500 --> 01:56:18.460
in [foreign words] who were
described as making ink

01:56:18.460 --> 01:56:22.020
and making wooden tablets.

01:56:22.020 --> 01:56:28.300
This is very interesting because
as Professor Hunwick mentioned the

01:56:28.300 --> 01:56:33.080
tablets, the Koranic tablets
are used either for talismans

01:56:33.080 --> 01:56:38.570
or they also are used as a
slate in Koranic schools.

01:56:38.570 --> 01:56:44.230
So these may indicate that
there were Koranic schools

01:56:44.230 --> 01:56:46.120
in [foreign words] during slavery.

01:56:46.120 --> 01:56:52.090 position:56%
And even though it may seem a little
bizarre this is not the only case.

01:56:52.090 --> 01:56:54.590
There were many Koranic schools

01:56:54.590 --> 01:56:58.000
which operated underground
in Brazil.

01:56:58.000 --> 01:57:02.470
And there was a big mass
enterprising in 1835 in Brazil.

01:57:02.470 --> 01:57:09.590
And the police went, of course,
through the houses of the Africans

01:57:09.590 --> 01:57:13.410
and they found the slaves and
they found books, et cetera.

01:57:13.410 --> 01:57:17.510
And it was revealed that those
schools had been operating

01:57:17.510 --> 01:57:18.810
for years.

01:57:18.810 --> 01:57:21.550
And I must say that there
were quite sophisticated.

01:57:21.550 --> 01:57:23.510
We are talking about
some people were free,

01:57:23.510 --> 01:57:25.880
but the majority of
them were slaves.

01:57:25.880 --> 01:57:33.660
I have an interesting quote by the
French Ambassador in Rio who wrote,

01:57:33.660 --> 01:57:40.230
and I quote, "The Koran was
sold in Rio at 15 to 25 queseros

01:57:40.230 --> 01:57:42.150
by the French [inaudible]
for showing [inaudible].

01:57:42.150 --> 01:57:44.400
We import copies from Europe.

01:57:44.400 --> 01:57:47.180
Slaves who appear to be
quite poor are willing

01:57:47.180 --> 01:57:50.520 position:56%
to make the greatest sacrifices to
acquire this volume, going into debt

01:57:50.520 --> 01:57:54.130
to do so, and sometimes taking a
year to pay off the bookseller.

01:57:54.130 --> 01:57:57.590
About a hundred copies of the
Koran are sold every year."

01:57:57.590 --> 01:58:02.840
So you can see that even though
people were enslaved what leads all

01:58:02.840 --> 01:58:07.090
time in urgent money they had,
they [inaudible] separated

01:58:07.090 --> 01:58:09.820
that to buying the Koran.

01:58:09.820 --> 01:58:13.510
We also have mentions of
Korans in the United States.

01:58:13.510 --> 01:58:19.260
Some were given by
priests to the Muslims.

01:58:19.260 --> 01:58:24.630
Some were smuggled,
if you will, here.

01:58:24.630 --> 01:58:29.290
There were also people who wrote
-- did not have access to a Koran,

01:58:29.290 --> 01:58:32.660
and they wrote their Koran by rote.

01:58:32.660 --> 01:58:34.830
I mean this is one thing that
people should be able to do

01:58:34.830 --> 01:58:38.130
after good Islamic education.

01:58:38.130 --> 01:58:44.170 position:56%
John [inaudible] that was mentioned
before wrote two copies of the Koran

01:58:44.170 --> 01:58:49.540
as he was going to London
back from -- back to Senegal.

01:58:49.540 --> 01:58:53.650
Another in Jamaica,
also that we know of,

01:58:53.650 --> 01:58:57.980
wrote his own copy of the Koran.

01:58:57.980 --> 01:59:00.950
[Inaudible] Muhammad from
Guinea, who was enslaved

01:59:00.950 --> 01:59:07.530
on [inaudible] wrote a
13-page manuscript in Arabic

01:59:07.530 --> 01:59:10.440
on paper that has been analyzed.

01:59:10.440 --> 01:59:16.510
And it's been shown that this
paper was manufactured in Italy

01:59:16.510 --> 01:59:19.490
for the Muslim market
of North Africa.

01:59:19.490 --> 01:59:25.220
So we have this Muslim from Guinea
in Georgia writing a manuscript

01:59:25.220 --> 01:59:30.050
on paper coming from
-- I mean made in Italy

01:59:30.050 --> 01:59:33.070
and which had been then sent to
North Africa and then smuggled

01:59:33.070 --> 01:59:38.470
in some way by what I call Islamic
networks of traders and sailors

01:59:38.470 --> 01:59:44.400
to Georgia, to a remote
plantation on the Sea Islands.

01:59:44.400 --> 01:59:46.160
What is important to see is

01:59:46.160 --> 01:59:51.120
that Muslim literacy
introduced a subversive element

01:59:51.120 --> 01:59:55.890
in those slave societies because
they were based on the idea

01:59:55.890 --> 01:59:59.060
that Africans were
kind of a sub-species,

01:59:59.060 --> 02:00:04.540
incapable of any intellectual
pursuit.

02:00:04.540 --> 02:00:06.150
So the idea was that,
well, you know,

02:00:06.150 --> 02:00:10.130
if these people came here
knowing how to read and write

02:00:10.130 --> 02:00:11.900
in Arabic, what does it mean?

02:00:11.900 --> 02:00:13.840
That there are schools in Africa.

02:00:13.840 --> 02:00:18.660
There's paper, there's ink,
there are teachers, students.

02:00:18.660 --> 02:00:23.220
So what about the idea that all
those people are just savages

02:00:23.220 --> 02:00:26.280
running around naked
hitting one another.

02:00:26.280 --> 02:00:31.990
So these opened questions in
the slave societies to the point

02:00:31.990 --> 02:00:37.650
that in many cases these
Muslims were Sub-Saharan Africans

02:00:37.650 --> 02:00:42.310
from Senegal, Guinea, Mali,
Sierra Leone, Nigeria, Ghana,

02:00:42.310 --> 02:00:48.050
were described as not being
Africans but as being Arabs.

02:00:48.050 --> 02:00:50.140
Now there was also another problem.

02:00:50.140 --> 02:00:54.130
The fact that paper
was smuggled out,

02:00:54.130 --> 02:00:58.270
books were also smuggled
in some way.

02:00:58.270 --> 02:01:01.810
And the fact that there
were Koranic schools --

02:01:01.810 --> 02:01:08.640
evidence that there was a well-run
organized underground community.

02:01:08.640 --> 02:01:13.310
And this community
could do something else

02:01:13.310 --> 02:01:18.020
than just pursue religious
and literary things.

02:01:18.020 --> 02:01:19.980
It could be used in a
more practical manner.

02:01:19.980 --> 02:01:25.590
And, of course, we've seen in
Guyana, in [foreign words],

02:01:25.590 --> 02:01:29.290
in Brazil, maybe not -- not in
the United States as we know of,

02:01:29.290 --> 02:01:34.840
but in other countries a
literacy in Arabic used

02:01:34.840 --> 02:01:37.810
by the slaves to plot revolts.

02:01:37.810 --> 02:01:47.970
From 1807 to 1835 there were many
Muslim conspiracies enterprising

02:01:47.970 --> 02:01:49.270
in Brazil.

02:01:49.270 --> 02:01:51.780
And we found -- I mean
the documents exist.

02:01:51.780 --> 02:01:53.150
They are still here today.

02:01:53.150 --> 02:02:00.200
And they show maps in Arabic --
maps, blueprints for the revolts,

02:02:00.200 --> 02:02:04.880
plans, et cetera, of people who
were planning those revolts.

02:02:04.880 --> 02:02:11.150 position:56%
They were also writing of another
type which were talismans as they --

02:02:11.150 --> 02:02:14.620
as you, as well as
I explained earlier.

02:02:14.620 --> 02:02:20.720
Those [inaudible] talismans
are mainly used by the Sufi

02:02:20.720 --> 02:02:23.620
and they are like, if
you will, I don't know,

02:02:23.620 --> 02:02:26.810
a saint medal in Christianity.

02:02:26.810 --> 02:02:30.310
They are not revered, but they
are supposed to, you know,

02:02:30.310 --> 02:02:33.660
to help the person who wears them.

02:02:33.660 --> 02:02:40.230
So what we've seen is that we have
many documents that are still --

02:02:40.230 --> 02:02:45.920 position:56%
exist today that were talisman,
that were used during those revolts.

02:02:45.920 --> 02:02:50.910
So, in fact, the talismans were
also kind of a weapon, if you will,

02:02:50.910 --> 02:02:55.570
that helped people feel
more secure and more sure

02:02:55.570 --> 02:03:01.530
of the outcome of the fight.

02:03:01.530 --> 02:03:06.900
So in the specific
situation of bondage,

02:03:06.900 --> 02:03:14.340
the literacy of the Africans
provided them an efficient tool

02:03:14.340 --> 02:03:15.940
that could be used as a weapon.

02:03:15.940 --> 02:03:19.190
And, of course, it was
discrete because the plans

02:03:19.190 --> 02:03:26.040
and the letters could go rather
far and very few slaveholders

02:03:26.040 --> 02:03:30.640 position:56%
and overseers wrote and read Arabic.

02:03:30.640 --> 02:03:34.700
On top of it some of those papers
were written in also Mandingo,

02:03:34.700 --> 02:03:38.810
written in the Arabic script.

02:03:38.810 --> 02:03:42.810
So it was very difficult
to decipher.

02:03:42.810 --> 02:03:49.260
Were there written
denunciations of slavery,

02:03:49.260 --> 02:03:56.890 position:56%
a kind of a protest literature if
you will in -- written by those men?

02:03:56.890 --> 02:03:58.190
We don't know.

02:03:58.190 --> 02:04:03.050
But what we can safely say
is that they were writing

02:04:03.050 --> 02:04:05.690
for other African [inaudible]
were enslaved,

02:04:05.690 --> 02:04:08.630
so there was no use
denouncing the situation.

02:04:08.630 --> 02:04:11.400
Everybody knew exactly what it was.

02:04:11.400 --> 02:04:15.250
But it's interesting to look
at texts which were written

02:04:15.250 --> 02:04:17.350
by African Muslims for the rest

02:04:17.350 --> 02:04:22.850
of the population,
the white population.

02:04:22.850 --> 02:04:25.850
I won't go into the
texts by Omar Said

02:04:25.850 --> 02:04:28.650
because I don't think
I would have time.

02:04:28.650 --> 02:04:33.950 position:56%
But I will just like to mention one
text which was written in 1834 by --

02:04:33.950 --> 02:04:37.180
a man from Mali was
enslaved in Jamaica,

02:04:37.180 --> 02:04:42.230
and he wrote his autobiography
in Arabic.

02:04:42.230 --> 02:04:47.220
He wrote the first version
while he was still in Jamaica

02:04:47.220 --> 02:04:49.960
and one part is interesting.

02:04:49.960 --> 02:04:55.360 position:56%
He wrote it and then he translated
it into English saying, and I quote,

02:04:55.360 --> 02:04:58.460
"We were three months at sea
before we arrived in Jamaica

02:04:58.460 --> 02:05:00.460
which was the beginning of bondage.

02:05:00.460 --> 02:05:04.570
I have no one to thank but
those who brought me here."

02:05:04.570 --> 02:05:05.870
End of quote.

02:05:05.870 --> 02:05:09.670
Now, the second version
he wrote when he was free

02:05:09.670 --> 02:05:14.030 position:56%
in London before going back to Mali.

02:05:14.030 --> 02:05:19.800
And the second version --
this paragraph reads --

02:05:19.800 --> 02:05:25.250
"This was the beginning of
my slavery until this day.

02:05:25.250 --> 02:05:29.880
I tasted the bitterness of slavery
from them and its oppressiveness.

02:05:29.880 --> 02:05:34.050
But praise be to God, under
whose power are all things."

02:05:34.050 --> 02:05:40.020
So once he was safe, he meant --
he made sure that people understood

02:05:40.020 --> 02:05:43.600
that some people were at
fault for him being enslaved.

02:05:43.600 --> 02:05:46.570 position:56%
And he was not thanking them at all.

02:05:46.570 --> 02:05:52.610
Can we say, as some
people mentioned,

02:05:52.610 --> 02:05:57.330
that the Muslims were
reclaiming their humanity

02:05:57.330 --> 02:05:58.750
through the [inaudible].

02:05:58.750 --> 02:06:01.710
I would say that people
have to be careful

02:06:01.710 --> 02:06:04.270
about saying things like that.

02:06:04.270 --> 02:06:08.090
We've seen -- I mean, many people
have seen Africans and blacks

02:06:08.090 --> 02:06:14.490
in general who [inaudible]
which for [inaudible]

02:06:14.490 --> 02:06:19.530
in 500 years of stereotypes.

02:06:19.530 --> 02:06:26.070
And there is no indication
at all that Muslims

02:06:26.070 --> 02:06:30.880
and non-Muslims were
enslaved in the Americas.

02:06:30.880 --> 02:06:33.180
[Inaudible] themselves
as not human at all.

02:06:33.180 --> 02:06:38.070
On the contrary, French,
Portuguese, Spanish, British,

02:06:38.070 --> 02:06:43.160
American sources consistently
mentioned that the Africans thought

02:06:43.160 --> 02:06:48.860
that they were equal or superior to
the people who had enslaved them.

02:06:48.860 --> 02:06:51.130
The Muslims have no reason
to think of themselves

02:06:51.130 --> 02:06:55.400
as pagans, as sub-humans.

02:06:55.400 --> 02:06:58.240
They certainly felt oppressed.

02:06:58.240 --> 02:07:00.460
They do not feel -- some of
them do not feel inferior

02:07:00.460 --> 02:07:05.660 position:56%
but they certainly felt oppressed as
human beings as well as [inaudible].

02:07:05.660 --> 02:07:12.100
And literacy had them fulfill
their needs, not only spiritual --

02:07:12.100 --> 02:07:15.060 position:56%
intellectual, political, and social.

02:07:15.060 --> 02:07:18.500
It was a marker, I think, of
identity, not of humanity,

02:07:18.500 --> 02:07:24.170
of identity as Muslims,
as clerics, as scholars.

02:07:24.170 --> 02:07:28.260
It meant continuing to be
in the situation of bondage

02:07:28.260 --> 02:07:32.130
where they had been before,
before they had status,

02:07:32.130 --> 02:07:34.660
before they had been
teachers or students.

02:07:34.660 --> 02:07:39.790
And they continued to remain so
even though they were enslaved.

02:07:39.790 --> 02:07:47.430
Given the number of Muslims
throughout the Americas,

02:07:47.430 --> 02:07:51.390
why don't we find more manuscripts?

02:07:51.390 --> 02:07:54.750
And, of course, I mean they
are the limitation that's,

02:07:54.750 --> 02:07:56.050
you know, you can imagine.

02:07:56.050 --> 02:08:02.780
But I must also say that more and
more manuscripts are cropping up.

02:08:02.780 --> 02:08:08.280
We found some recently in
Jamaica and in Trinidad.

02:08:08.280 --> 02:08:12.800
Besides the Omar [inaudible]
there are hundreds

02:08:12.800 --> 02:08:16.460
of manuscripts in Brazil.

02:08:16.460 --> 02:08:21.420
And as the topic becomes more --

02:08:21.420 --> 02:08:25.850
I mean as more and more scholars
are looking into this topic,

02:08:25.850 --> 02:08:29.240
more and more things
are being discovered

02:08:29.240 --> 02:08:33.810
that were there all along
just in boxes somewhere.

02:08:33.810 --> 02:08:45.050
And you know, to conclude, I will
say that a tradition of reading

02:08:45.050 --> 02:08:47.160
and writing, which in some areas

02:08:47.160 --> 02:08:52.580
that being established 500 years
even more the slave trade started

02:08:52.580 --> 02:08:56.530
found a new utility in America.

02:08:56.530 --> 02:08:58.900
Islam was the fourth behind that.

02:08:58.900 --> 02:09:04.660
But literacy here had
its own dynamics.

02:09:04.660 --> 02:09:08.060
It served also other
purposes than just reading

02:09:08.060 --> 02:09:10.610
of the Koran and the text.

02:09:10.610 --> 02:09:17.480
In the very harsh [inaudible] were
that they were forced to live in,

02:09:17.480 --> 02:09:20.040
the literate Africans used
their knowledge to defend

02:09:20.040 --> 02:09:24.080
and protect themselves, to regain
control through, for example,

02:09:24.080 --> 02:09:27.500
the talisman and the revolt, over
their lives and over their --

02:09:27.500 --> 02:09:30.320
the present and future
of their communities.

02:09:30.320 --> 02:09:35.780
And they also tried
to get their freedom.

02:09:35.780 --> 02:09:41.030
Their knowledge may have
seemed worthless in these --

02:09:41.030 --> 02:09:47.560
in the Western environment, but
it proved to be extremely useful

02:09:47.560 --> 02:09:52.170
as well as extremely
threatening to the enslavers.

02:09:52.170 --> 02:09:56.300
And those are not the only things

02:09:56.300 --> 02:10:00.140
that the African Muslims
have left in the Americas.

02:10:00.140 --> 02:10:07.100 position:56%
There are many others that can still
be found today in the religions even

02:10:07.100 --> 02:10:12.250
of people of African descent
who are not Muslims today.

02:10:12.250 --> 02:10:19.430
As mentioned also earlier,
Vodou has some very distinctive

02:10:19.430 --> 02:10:22.180
Islamic elements.

02:10:22.180 --> 02:10:28.590
So does Santeria and Candomble,
as well as other religions.

02:10:28.590 --> 02:10:34.200
So for 400 and sometimes 500 years,

02:10:34.200 --> 02:10:38.260
the African Muslims have
been a cultural, social,

02:10:38.260 --> 02:10:40.940
and spiritual force in America.

02:10:40.940 --> 02:10:44.240
They have left their mark,
including their written mark,

02:10:44.240 --> 02:10:48.950
in a society that negated
and rejected them.

02:10:48.950 --> 02:10:50.720
They were Africans,
they were Muslims.

02:10:50.720 --> 02:10:54.070
They became African Americans.

02:10:54.070 --> 02:10:59.240
And their story has to be
heard an unearthed if we want

02:10:59.240 --> 02:11:03.490
to better understand the various
cultures that have made America.

02:11:03.490 --> 02:11:06.440
Thank you [applause].

02:11:06.440 --> 02:11:07.960
&gt;&gt; Prosser Gifford:
