02:15:21.750 --> 02:15:26.870
So what I'm going to do very
briefly today is give you kind

02:15:26.870 --> 02:15:33.370
of an overview of the African
American Islamic experience.

02:15:33.370 --> 02:15:36.510
And as I was researching some
information for this presentation

02:15:36.510 --> 02:15:38.710
at the Chamburg [assumed
spelling], I realized that there's

02:15:38.710 --> 02:15:46.120 position:56%
such a shortage of material about
such a profound and dynamic subject.

02:15:47.460 --> 02:15:53.260
And as I listened to Yonne Haddad
and Professor Akbar Ahmed talk

02:15:53.260 --> 02:16:00.010
about the idea of 9/11, in many
instances within the discourse

02:16:00.010 --> 02:16:02.400
within the Islamic community,

02:16:02.400 --> 02:16:07.910
we are framing our
experience pre- and post-9/11.

02:16:07.910 --> 02:16:10.920
And we are not really clear
on what to make of the change

02:16:10.920 --> 02:16:14.300
that is taking place after 9/11.

02:16:14.300 --> 02:16:20.210
But I think it's ironic around
the idea of civilization project

02:16:20.210 --> 02:16:24.810 position:56%
and the idea of civilizational
dialogue, as Dr. Ahmed talked about,

02:16:24.810 --> 02:16:30.860
is that we have to actually go back
to a period in our history to refer

02:16:30.860 --> 02:16:37.370
to a point or a period where we
can draw from that will allow us

02:16:37.370 --> 02:16:39.040
to be more civilized
with each other.

02:16:39.040 --> 02:16:47.230
I think that is indicative of the
failure of our ability to cope

02:16:47.230 --> 02:16:55.000 position:56%
with the reality of the plurality of
our existence here on this planet.

02:16:55.000 --> 02:17:00.170
Having said that, I would also
like to say about the idea of 9/11,

02:17:00.170 --> 02:17:06.820
African Americans are not
new to racial profiling.

02:17:06.820 --> 02:17:10.780
The term was coined
by our existence.

02:17:10.780 --> 02:17:13.190
African Americans are not new --

02:17:13.190 --> 02:17:16.020
we're not neophyte to
the idea of oppression,

02:17:16.020 --> 02:17:20.500
and marginalization,
and misrepresentation.

02:17:20.500 --> 02:17:23.770
This all happened pre-9/11.

02:17:23.770 --> 02:17:27.480
This has been the sum total of
our existence and our struggle

02:17:27.480 --> 02:17:31.050
as we strived, and continue to
strive, to establish a sense

02:17:31.050 --> 02:17:37.000
of social justice for people
in general in America.

02:17:37.000 --> 02:17:41.020
This is not new to us.

02:17:41.020 --> 02:17:47.370
And as an activist scholar -- I
was going to say scholar activist,

02:17:47.370 --> 02:17:49.050 position:56%
but really I am an activist scholar.

02:17:49.050 --> 02:17:54.780
More activist than scholar,
actually, because I feel

02:17:54.780 --> 02:17:59.980
like Gramsci has told us,
somewhat as -- when he talks --

02:17:59.980 --> 02:18:02.640
when he characterizes
the organic intellectual,

02:18:02.640 --> 02:18:08.500
that theory is grounded
and actualized in praxis.

02:18:08.500 --> 02:18:11.090
So having had the experience
of working

02:18:11.090 --> 02:18:14.410
within the African American Muslim
community for over 20 years,

02:18:14.410 --> 02:18:17.320
it has actualized much
of my understanding

02:18:17.320 --> 02:18:20.460
of the theoretical framework.

02:18:24.570 --> 02:18:30.700
Let me say that as African
American Muslims, there is no way

02:18:30.700 --> 02:18:37.040 position:56%
that I could convey to you the
trials, tribulations, the struggles,

02:18:37.040 --> 02:18:41.520
the difficulties, the pain, the
anguish, the contradictions,

02:18:41.520 --> 02:18:52.720 position:56%
the alienation, the marginalization
of a people who have embraced Islam.

02:18:52.720 --> 02:18:57.930 position:56%
And after embracing this great faith
of 1/5 of the entire human race,

02:18:57.930 --> 02:19:04.940
now have taken on another burden
where we are, in many instances,

02:19:04.940 --> 02:19:10.650
doubly margined -- doubly
marginalized for being black --

02:19:10.650 --> 02:19:16.130
punished for being black in a
society that privileges whiteness,

02:19:16.130 --> 02:19:19.450
that -- where racism continues
to permeate individual minds,

02:19:19.450 --> 02:19:24.220
and consciousness, and
imaginations, and institutions.

02:19:24.220 --> 02:19:28.010
And being Muslim in a society
where Ibn Said characterizes

02:19:28.010 --> 02:19:31.820
that the Islam that is represented
or, quote, misrepresented,

02:19:31.820 --> 02:19:39.670
or covered, or miscovered [sic],
is more about a conception

02:19:39.670 --> 02:19:46.230
and a construction of a
demonized group rather

02:19:46.230 --> 02:19:51.600
than the profound religion that is
represented by such a large number

02:19:51.600 --> 02:19:58.440
of people, a great religion that
is embraced by such a large number

02:19:58.440 --> 02:20:02.730
of people on this planet,
a religion that teaches

02:20:02.730 --> 02:20:05.840
such beautiful teachings of love,
and compassion, and understanding,

02:20:05.840 --> 02:20:09.400
and respect for human beings,
and respect for human life,

02:20:09.400 --> 02:20:14.920
and respect for the dignity of
human beings and human existence.

02:20:18.250 --> 02:20:22.760 position:56%
My topic was, of course,
contemporary African American Islam.

02:20:22.760 --> 02:20:26.760
And for the few minutes that I have
left here, I want to talk to you

02:20:26.760 --> 02:20:33.120
about some aspects of that.

02:20:33.120 --> 02:20:36.380
When we say contemporary African
American Islam, we have to --

02:20:36.380 --> 02:20:39.640
I have to make a disclaimer
because the concept

02:20:39.640 --> 02:20:45.010
of contemporary African American
Islam is problematic for Muslims,

02:20:45.010 --> 02:20:48.520
because in most cases Muslims would
argue that there's no such thing

02:20:48.520 --> 02:20:52.660
as African American Islam, nor is
there such a thing as Arab Islam,

02:20:52.660 --> 02:20:57.890
or Pakistani Islam, that
there really is one Islam.

02:21:00.590 --> 02:21:05.190 position:56%
But I would argue that that one
divine and revealed religion and way

02:21:05.190 --> 02:21:08.040
of life that was revealed
to the Prophet Muhammad,

02:21:08.040 --> 02:21:10.030
peace and blessings be
upon him, by the Creator

02:21:10.030 --> 02:21:16.610 position:56%
of the universe immediately changes
as soon as human beings claim agency

02:21:16.610 --> 02:21:22.950 position:56%
over it, as soon as individual human
beings embrace it, it now is changed

02:21:22.950 --> 02:21:28.340
from the pristine purity of its
revelation to its interpreters

02:21:28.340 --> 02:21:33.460
and interlocutors who nuance
it with their culture,

02:21:33.460 --> 02:21:35.520
who nuance it with
their hermeneutics,

02:21:35.520 --> 02:21:43.330
who nuance it with their
worldview and continue the process

02:21:43.330 --> 02:21:45.090
of its misrepresentation.

02:21:45.090 --> 02:21:49.030
Not only does the Western
media often misrepresent Islam,

02:21:49.030 --> 02:21:53.220
but in many instances Muslims
themselves misrepresent Islam.

02:21:53.220 --> 02:21:58.470
So when I talk about
African American Islam,

02:21:58.470 --> 02:22:02.490
what I'm really saying is
Islam among African Americans.

02:22:02.490 --> 02:22:06.660
I think that is a much more
appropriate title And I don't need

02:22:06.660 --> 02:22:09.070
to go into detail, and I don't
have time to go into detail

02:22:09.070 --> 02:22:11.600 position:56%
about the delineation of the history

02:22:11.600 --> 02:22:13.880
or chronicling the
history of the experience.

02:22:13.880 --> 02:22:16.710
I have basically divided the
experience into three phases.

02:22:16.710 --> 02:22:21.880
One is what I call the
pre-emancipation phase,

02:22:21.880 --> 02:22:24.170
African Muslims in
antebellum America.

02:22:24.170 --> 02:22:27.560
In this experience alone
one sentence will, I think,

02:22:27.560 --> 02:22:29.870
be appropriate for you
to capture the essence

02:22:29.870 --> 02:22:32.030
of what the experience is about.

02:22:32.030 --> 02:22:40.190
The slaves, a Muslim who left the
mosque in the Senegambian region

02:22:40.190 --> 02:22:47.120
to go home to his family,
captured, chained, enslaved,

02:22:47.120 --> 02:22:51.900 position:56%
taken from his homeland, his family,
his loved ones, his community,

02:22:51.900 --> 02:22:56.130
and brought to the shores of
North America to be dehumanized,

02:22:56.130 --> 02:23:00.350
to be demasculated [sic] and sold.

02:23:00.350 --> 02:23:06.130
And out of this horrific
experience, this individual --

02:23:06.130 --> 02:23:09.590 position:56%
or these individuals like Omar,
like Saliba Lada [assumed spelling],

02:23:09.590 --> 02:23:12.730
like so many others that we
have not even discovered,

02:23:12.730 --> 02:23:16.560
but whose spirit we embody,
particularly as African Americans,

02:23:16.560 --> 02:23:18.710
who lived that experience.

02:23:18.710 --> 02:23:21.720
These people were able to
maintain the Islamic practice

02:23:21.720 --> 02:23:25.900
within the context of the
horrific experience of slavery.

02:23:25.900 --> 02:23:28.460
That's pre-emancipation slavery.

02:23:28.460 --> 02:23:31.390
Painful, painful.

02:23:31.390 --> 02:23:36.220
There are not even enough texts
to explain the pain that existed

02:23:36.220 --> 02:23:38.070
to the experience of slavery.

02:23:38.070 --> 02:23:41.720
One can read it, but the
reality of the experience

02:23:41.720 --> 02:23:44.830
of it is something
altogether different.

02:23:44.830 --> 02:23:48.900
The second phase is what I call
the early Islamic communities,

02:23:48.900 --> 02:23:52.580
from 1900 to 1960.

02:23:52.580 --> 02:23:54.420
And in this particular phase

02:23:54.420 --> 02:23:57.430
of the Islamic development
we see the evolution

02:23:57.430 --> 02:24:00.280
of what I call proto-Islamic
movements.

02:24:00.280 --> 02:24:03.610
And I call them proto- to
qualify the fact that many

02:24:03.610 --> 02:24:08.210 position:56%
of these movements did not
articulate nor practice the orthodox

02:24:08.210 --> 02:24:11.750
teachings of Al-Islam, but
in fact appropriated --

02:24:11.750 --> 02:24:16.770
selectively appropriated various
theological teachings of Islam,

02:24:16.770 --> 02:24:23.440
to use, to construct, to
develop, to construct tools --

02:24:23.440 --> 02:24:29.250
as tools to be deployed to
oppose racism and oppression.

02:24:29.250 --> 02:24:35.650
And within that period of time we
did have individual communities

02:24:35.650 --> 02:24:39.590
that evolved and emerged,
that became closer --

02:24:39.590 --> 02:24:44.150
that emerged closer to what
we call the Islamic orthodoxy.

02:24:44.150 --> 02:24:48.080
So movements like the Nation of
-- I mean, the Noble Drew Ali,

02:24:48.080 --> 02:24:52.820
the Moorish Science Temple, even
organizations like Marcus Garvey

02:24:52.820 --> 02:24:56.350
who was influenced by Duse
Mohamed Ali when he went to London,

02:24:56.350 --> 02:24:59.130
before he came to the United
States, that Muslims involved

02:24:59.130 --> 02:25:04.580
in the Marcus Garvey
movement, Muslims, of course,

02:25:04.580 --> 02:25:08.350
African Americans,
emerging from that movement

02:25:08.350 --> 02:25:11.290
into what is called the Nation
of Islam with Fard Muhammad

02:25:11.290 --> 02:25:17.280
and eventually Elijah Muhammad,
using the teaching of Islam

02:25:17.280 --> 02:25:21.720
to fight oppression and racism.

02:25:21.720 --> 02:25:26.740 position:56%
And the final phase is the phase
that I call the contemporary period,

02:25:26.740 --> 02:25:31.170
which is basically
from 1960 until now.

02:25:31.170 --> 02:25:35.110
If you look at the movements
in 1960, the Dar al-Islam,

02:25:35.110 --> 02:25:38.560
the Muslim International
Brotherhood, Sheik Daud --

02:25:38.560 --> 02:25:40.900
